text: Idris does make a decent representation of Roland. Unfortunately, the rest of it is a disappointment: no other companions in sight, Jake elevated to main character even if he was originally pretty much a deconstruction of what a child would really be able to do in a dark fantasy plot (that is, mostly just suffer), too much focus on New freaking York. King's trademark fascination with characters on the fringes of society and the dark American underbelly is all gone. Journey across a post-apocalyptic dimension with isolated quirky communes, gone. Heck, Eddie is gone.   Instead, we get slo-mo gun kata. Boo freaking hoo.

text: Elba certainly has the charisma and grit to play Roland, and Mcconaughey definitely resembles what I saw the Man in Black to be. As far as the source material, this is a sequel to a series, that has a multiverse, cyclical repetition, and divergent timelines.  If they said it was a sequel and then changed nothing, the would be worth getting mad about. As far as Detta Walker and Roland, Detta was universally rude. And she'll probably still use race against Roland and Eddie. I understand changing the source material bothers people, but the Dark Tower series is based heavily on everything changing, other worlds, etc. Does Roland being black really seem such a radical departure?

text: I always thought one of the coolest scenes in the book was when Eddie had to shoot his way out of a drug house butt-naked. That's courageous. But the entire Gunslinger mythos has always inspired me for some odd reason. To have guns that are forged from the swords of Arthur Eld, to wield them as the Gunslinger did, to have been raised in a culture where the Gun is the way of life...all of these things create an almost mystical world full of technology, dereliction and decadence from a time not entirely separate from our own. It's almost as though the things we've discarded have fallen through to Roland's world. It's where the pillars of our own universe--and many others--are firmly rooted. I don't know...I just feel like we're all looking for our own Dark Tower and some are more driven than others. And there are those of us who are driven to extremes that some would say border on lunacy. Whatever our Dark Tower might be--whatever it is we're looking for--sometimes we have to discard the things most precious to us to find it, to scale the stairs and to reach the top. I know Roland the Gunslinger lost a lot in the books. Love and sense of self being but two things out of many. He's seen a lot and he has a kind of 'frontier wisdom' that I hope comes through in this cinematic adaptation. I'm holding out for "Cool Blue Shooter's Eyes" such as Roland had in the book. Roland, for me, has become an archetype for one who has lost it all just trying to find his way in the world, utilizing skill sets that some of us may view as archaic but that in his world are indicative of an old and ancient nobility. The books got a little slow, at times, and were somewhat difficult to finish. But I did finish them. All the way. To the very End. Be careful what you make your Dark Tower out to be.

text: There are going to be a lot of haters. I was a little miffed at first that they cast an african american actor to play Roland because he is so clearly described as a white man with bright blue eyes, but Idris Elba is a spectacular Actor. If you haven't seen Luther then you don't even know... That being said - true fans of the books will let this slide. They know that this is not a direct adaptation but a sequel. And that many things can change on different levels of the tower -  and at different cycles (in the books 2 non-relative characters are blood brothers in a different version of New York so a families race changing is not hard to believe at all). I have no problem with it, and I for one, have gone from cautiously optimistic to overtly hopeful. I mean look at it! We get to see Lud, River Crossing, Steven Deschain, it even looks like they didn't skimp on the Dutch Hill Mansion Demon afterall...  Screw the haters. This movie is going to be awesome.

My one true fear about this movie is that it will turn a series that was full of well rounded and truly deep characters into a standard popcorn action flick, just keeping a few of the more memorable lines from the source material.

text: This looks awesome!!! I love the books and I'm happy to see a gunslinger on the big screen.  I've read them soo many times.  Movies are not books and books are not movies.  When did a movie ever faithfully recreate a book?  Never.  It's not possible because the mediums are completely different and a movie is an artists interpretation of a book.  Much like how you may have envisioned Eddie or Susannah/Odetta when you read the books is not the same as how I envisioned them.  Stephen King has said that this is more like a sequel to the books than a film adaptation.  That's great!!! Keep the books pure and give us an additional part of the story.  Spoiler for those who didn't read the books, but the story goes on.  As the books say, "There are other worlds than these".  This world we see here is different than the world we know from the books.  It doesn't mean it's horrible or wrong.  Remember the end of the final book and the alternate world with "certain" people alive and well.  Indeed, there are more worlds than just the world we read about.

text: Also to people complaining that it's not a direct adaption: that's.. literally the point? It's not an adaption. It's a continuation/sequel. It's NOT the original journey Roland made to the tower. At the end, he restarted with the Horn of Eld, the entire point being that it was a loop where small things could eventually break the cycle as Roland learned. That's what this journey is: the next in the cycle. It's LITERALLY a new story. (For y'all who wanna interpret the book however: this being a new cycle was confirmed by SK himself so like, also chill.)

text: DARK TOWER BOOK SPOILERS AHEAD, AVOID:   A lot of people are crying foul because SPE is turning this into seemingly another shoot'em up that doesn't follow the plot of the book and I am in that camp. I realized while discussing that with a friend that SPE has an out to soothe the rage of the people who have read and love the books: they can explain it away as another cycle of Roland's journey. Every time Roland goes through the door things change and it's inferred he's gone through the door many many times. SPE can just claim this is one of a near infinite number of cycles where things are just different from the one we read. If SPE is smart they'll add this, subtly, into the movie, in a way only people who read the books would really get.

text: In fairness, they included The Men in Low Coats, what I can only assume was The Wolves of the Calla and references to The Crimson King.  They've cut out Eddie, Susannah, Callahan, Oy, Sheemie the special needs mystic, Ted, Andy the Messenger Robot, Allie, High Speech,  the AIDS vampires, Calvin Tower and the other librarian, The Rose, the field of Roses, Jack Mort, Enrico Balazar, All twelve beam guardians, Gan, todash, the entire multiverse because it's too confusing, the talking sentient psychopath train called Blaine, the succubus that keeps having sex with everyone, Mordred Deschain, Rhea of the C√∂os, Roonts, The Slow Mutants, Cort, Vannay, David the Eagle, Roland's mother, Richard Sayre, Jamie DeCurry, Cuthbert Allgood, and Alain, the mutated creatures and crops, Brown, Arthur Eld, Zoltan, Susan Delgado, Maerlyn's Rainbow, Taheen, Reap, lobstrosities, Henry Dean, The Tick-Tock Man, John Farson, roughly nineteen aliases to The Man in Black, The Old Ones, The Gingerbread House, Dinky and Stephen King himself along with hundreds of other major and minor characters. (Feel free to name others I've missed.)  But at the heart of the film, it's about a post-apocalypse western/sci-fi with the set design of Wild, Wild West. That's all you need.  I'm going to enjoy this film for what it is, because it is impossible to make anything but an adaptation of King's Dark Tower. The literature is Game of Thrones on bath salts. If you've read the series, you wouldn't even WANT to see a movie or series that was true to The Dark Tower's mythos.   Cowboy man with magic guns. versus. Evil man who's evil. Sign me up.

text: I couldn't care less what the race of the actor portraying Roland is, as long as the characters personality and wise charm are correctly presented then I will be happy. Idris Elba is a fantastic actor and I think he will do a good job with the character.  However the tone and feel of this trailer seems way off from the books, like by allot. The books were always more character driven with allot of word building throughout. They tended to be a fairly slow burn with a couple of decent action scenes spread around, that's how it was in every book. The first book in the series, though it has been awhile sense I read it, only had like one big action scene in it, the one right at the start.   This trailer seems to show off what looks to be a fairly generic action movie, and is way off from any of the books. Hell, *Spoilers* don't read if haven't read the books yet, In the book Roland doesn't even go to our more modern world until the second book, and he didn't go there with the kid, and it was after he got his fingers on his right hand tore off, which then got infected, and he nearly died because of it.  I won't judge the movie based on the trailer, as I truly hope the movie is good, but if what I'm to expect from the movie is similar to what's mostly being portrayed in this trailer then I am going to be extremely disappointed.

Hearts in Atlantis, the Windcatcher - both excellent novels. Both horrendous films... And it kinda looks like that kid can't act? No offense... It's a really hard part for a kid to play. Here's an excerpt from the original story:  "Jake opened his folder to take a final look at what he had written on the topic My Understanding of Truth.  He was genuinely interested in this, because he could no more remember writing his Final Essay, than he could remember studying for his French final.    He looked at the title page with puzzlement and growing unease.  MY UNDERSTANDING OF TRUTH, By Jake Chambers, was neatly typed and centered on the sheet, and that was all right, but he had for some reason pasted two photographs below it.  One was of a door - he thought it might be the one at Number 10, Downing Street, in London - and the other was of an Amtrak train.  They were color shots, undoubtedly culled from some magazine.  Why did I do that?  And when did I do that?  He turned the page and stared down at the first page of his Final Essay, unable to believe or understand what he was seeing.  Then, as understanding began to trickle through his shock, he felt an escalating sense of horror.  It had finally happened; he had finally lost enough of his mind so that other people would be able to tell."

text: There are going to be people that hate us, but for those of us who have read the books, and have a special love for them, we will not like this like y'all would. Within 1 minute so much was wrong with the story that I could barely keep watching. The dark tower series is a very deep, confusing and twisting system of books that have the reader constantly wondering what will happen. Not to mention most of the stories happen in multiple storytelling ways, and much of what is found out about the settings is learned through the main characters thoughts only. The books make  you care for the characters in a way because so much of the series do not have a straight forward emotional statement from the characters. Even the main character speaks about his emotionlessness throughout. It makes me sad to see a book series so close to my heart altered in such a way as to take away from the original

text: Although a major Constant Reader of King and fan of the book series, I won't¬†spend my money on this film. For most of my life I have read about Roland, a guy with pale blue eyes who resembles Clint Eastwood's gunfighter characters. Now they want me to watch a guy who does not resemble that character in the slightest play the role? So sorry, but cannot do it. Elba is a fine actor but he just doesn't fit this role, especially¬†after so many repetitions of what the Gunslinger looks like in the novels (the phrase "faded blue eyes" has been used over & over). Too far from the path on this one for me to suspend disbelief. I will be thinking of this major flaw the whole time since I am so familiar with the story. Maybe it will be OK for those who haven't read the books.

text: I just spent about twenty minutes reading all the comments, just to get a better gauge on what other people's opinions on this trailer are, their insights into the discrepancies between the books and this film, etc, etc.  So I've read that people are considering it a "sequel-ish", being that time travel, teleportation and the ending of the literary saga allows for such things after Roland passes through the Tower Door.  But these don't really interest me as explanations, nor does this film being some amalgamation of Books 1, 5, and some new re-imagining that some Hollywood scriptwriters put together.  Seeing this just confirms my fears that I won't want to see something I've looked forward to, and that's not saying it will be a bad film, it's just not the film I want to see.    This reminds me a lot of I Am Legend, since Hollywood has made that incredible story into a film three times, and all three were ok films, just ok at best; but they never seem interested in capturing the grit and horror of the book.  That's what this looks like, it looks like a good film for most people unfamiliar with the source material, but from what I as an insanely committed fan of the book series hoped for, I'm just not seeing it in this trailer, nor have I felt it when reading about the making of this film.  To everyone who see's it, I hope it's good and you enjoy it, but I just know I won't, so I just won't ever watch this.  The books will have to be my wealth spring, since it looks like Hollywood has miles to go yet, before doing this epic true justice.

text: As a black man, I know that just because someone disagrees with a black actor playing a character that is written white doesn't mean they are racist!  Some are, but most just want to be true to the written word they have already experienced.  I love Elba and I think he is awesome but, i don't think he should be the next James Bond either.  James Bond is a white secret agent - always has been!  While he's a supporting character, not a main character, imagine they remade Rocky and made Apollo Creed white???  I know I'd be pissed!  Not because I'm a racist! Rather, Apollo was originally a black character - and I liked it that way.  I be pissed not because they chose a white guy.  More so that they changed the context of the story that I enjoyed.   What really needs to happen is black writers need to come up with better story lines that will appeal to broader audiences.  This years "Get Out" is a prime example.  We have to figure out a way to get stories other than gangs, drugs and violence on the big screen.   Then black actors would have more prospects and opportunities to play interesting characters that are written for them.  I know Hollywood is f***'d up but it can be done! BTW - I'm gonna still see the movie because it looks interesting.

text: As far as character selection goes, while Idris Elba is a good actor, it is known to those who read the books that Roland Deschain was based on Clint Eastwood.   Clint Eastwood is old, he's 86 now.  A suitable replacement would be Viggo Mortensen.  He has the look, and he's a good actor.  Plus, he's 58 now, and the only time Roland was ever truly portrayed as young, was in memory flashbacks and in Wizard and Glass and in The Wind Through the Keyhole.    And for everyone saying Roland was never truly portrayed as white, yes he was in Drawing of the Three when Detta referred to him as a Honk Mofa and also sensed his complete whiteness, and in The Dark Tower it was while he was with Irene Tassenbaum that it was further revealed that not only was he white, he may have had Native American blood as well.  And for everyone else saying it has already severely deviated from the books, yes it has!  It was supposed to!  https://twitter.com/stephenking/status/733244613000069120?lang=en  If you didn't actually get to the end of the books, you missed a major clue.  This is a continuation of the book series, and that has been acknowledged.  This is not a typical film adaptation.  This is using film to continue and hopefully conclude one of the best series I ever read, and what can easily be argued as the best work of Stephen Kings writing career.

text: As a black woman, I'm MUCH more upset about the removal of Susannah/Odetta/Detta than anything. Where are she and Eddie?! I can sort of understand the upset about Roland not being white, because there are SO many descriptions of him appearance on the book, and if Susannah and Eddie were in the story, it would change some of the dynamic (but only to an extent: if Stephen King is for it, I'm 100% cool with Idris Elba, he's an amazing actor.) I just don't understand how they could take something as fully-realized and laboriously descriptive as TDT series and relegate it to some big-budget sci-fi action blockbuster that takes FAR too little from the source. Why did they have to deviate so much, to the point where it's nearly unrecognizable?  I'm probably still going to go see it, and I may even enjoy it... but it's not The Dark Tower.

text: So the Dark Tower looks like it's going to be as different from the books as casting decisions were. I know it was King's call all around but this complete reimagining of the Dark Tower is going to have an impact when it comes to bringing in new fans through this film. Elba is a strong choice for this role and what I saw here his work as Roland definitely fascinates me and I will go see this film, but for decades Roland was a kind of Clint Eastwood doppleganger, how come nobody is complaining about black washing a figure from a major twentieth century franchise which has an already cult like fanbase, has become a part of our shared cultural mythology in it's own way? text: I understand The Dark Tower was in development hell for the longest time, and I understand this is a sequel to the books.  That being said, I am upset because I, and I'm sure many others, wanted an adaptation of the books.  Before anyone starts responding, just please hear me out.  I envisioned this story to be told in both movie and television formats.  That is a bit risky given the amount of material, but it can work.  Books 1, 3, 5, & 7 would serve as movies, with the 7th book being split into two movies.  There are five movies there.  Books 2, 4, and 6 would be adapted into three television series, preferably on HBO or Showtime.  There are three seasons there.  This would have to be filmed consecutively as LOTR was to account for the length of time the book series runs.  This is possible, and unfortunately Hollywood got their money-grubbing hands on a beloved series.

It‚Äôs there that he discovers that he‚Äôs gone on this quest before, many times, and is sent back to the beginning of his journey by a being known as Gan each time. In prior quests, Roland had left the Horn of Eld with a dying compatriot after a battle. In this latest version of the quest, he kept it with him, which changes things for the next cycle of the story.  The implication here is that the film is set after The Dark Tower (the novel): Roland has been sent back to the beginning of his quest, and the events of The Gunslinger will play out in a slightly different way. As we saw in the trailer, he meets Jake Chambers, and is going after The Man in Black. So, the film could essentially be an adaptation of The Gunslinger, but a continuation of the story at the same time.

text: Ok, so it seems that this entire movie will have nothing to do with the original story from the books. That is very disheartening, as I wanted to see that story be brought to life at some point.  But it would at least partially explain why Roland is suddenly black, because the Dark Tower is basically holding the multiverse together and in one of those worlds, Roland could defintely be black. I'm ok with that now.  But there's still a lot about this trailer that makes me fear that this will just be a run-of-the-mill overly stylised action movie which compresses too much of the mythology of TDT into an incoherent mess and is more concerned with over the top action-scenes. Gunslinger shooting without looking? One of the essential parts of the mantra Elba is reciting in this trailer is "I do not aim with my hand, [...] I aim with my eye". Gunslingers are great shots, but they aren't Jedi. Same goes for the silly mid-air reload. I'm now willing to give this movie a chance, but my expectations after this trailer are VERY low. I do however like the eastereggs about other King works in the movie, and I think McConaughey as Walter/MIB and the actor they have for Jake are fitting for their roles. I'm just still sad that they didn't try to adapt the original source material. I would've loved to see the original Ka-tet in action. Without Eddie and Susannah, there's just something missing.

text: Idris Elba's casting as Roland is an obvious red herring to stir up Internet controversy so that people will go out to see the movie to prove that they aren't racist. The producers obviously took way too many creative liberties with the source material and the end result is inevitably going to be mediocre. I have a sneaking suspicion that this movie was made by jamming a bunch of half-assed dark tower references into some rejected fantasy-action movie script that a studio exec found at the bottom of his file cabinet next to the baggies of cocaine and used condoms. the only purpose this movie serves is to prevent the studio from losing the movie rights to the dark tower. Remember that shitty Fantastic 4 movie that caused the exact same controversy by casting a black guy as the human torch? That movie was made at the same time that Fox was about to lose the rights to Fantastic 4. It's a shame that Idris Elba got conned into starring in this abomination. He's a great actor and I hope this doesn't destroy his career.

text: There's definitely a few problems here in my opinion. My issue specifically is with the nature of the dark tower that is depicted in this. I feel like in the books it was something beyond comprehension, a constant thing in the background which drives everyone in the books almost to the point of obsession, the centre of everything that is. It just seems almost a little clich√© the way they depict it here, although It's just a trailer so that might be an early judgment. I also feel the series wasn't as focused on fight scenes as much as this, it was always sudden bursts of violence which almost shocked the reader. Obviously they have also smashed many parts of the book into one story which is a little disappointing but understandable because of the length the movie can't really do an epic like the Dark Tower series justice.   I don't know what all the complaining about Roland is about though, Idris definitely got the feeling of the character, I don't think his race is really an issue. It's pretty refreshing actually, and if the movie is trying to keep a distance from the exact story of the books then it does make sense to change it up a little. To be honest I'm just happy that this will more than likely encourage a wider audience to get into the books. I feel they never really got the praise they deserved.  Hoping for some Lobstrosities tho, that would be great.

text: Ok so as a fan of the original book series, (as well as the ones that are tie ins, like insomnia, everything's eventual, hearts in Atlantis, etc), I can understand the frustration of some of the commentors. But there are a few things to keep in mind here. As for Roland being black in this movie, I too did have concerns because what ramifications would that have on Susannah's character since much of what made her who she was was an undertone of isolation being the not only the only female but also the only black member of their ka-tet. In this movie that's going to be a non issue since her character is not in it. Now whether this becomes a franchise & they eventually do more movies or not may change that. That being said, Roland is a rather difficult character to cast for & Idris is one of the few people whom can pull it off. So I think it's only fair to give him a chance. Additionally, you also have to remember, for those that really DID read the books, Roland has the horn of Eld in this movie. that is very important because the only point in which he has it in the books is when he is standing in the Mohine desert AFTER reaching the tower at the end of the 7th book. in the story arc of the books, the horn of eld was lost on Jericho hill & only returned to him at the end as he began a new cycle, immediately forgetting the last. this movie IS that new cycle. sure I wanted to see Eddie, Susannah, the people of Calla Byrn Sturgis, Callahan, Patrick Danville, even John Farson, all those people too. The raid on Algul Siento, Jake & Callahan storming the Dixie Pig, ol double ugly getting eaten alive by monstrosities, & maybe that is all still to come in future movies. or maybe that will be in a tv show format where honestly books tend to better translate to film anyway. however it's clear that this movie is not an adaption of the 7 cannon novels, but a continuation from where they ended. this movie is starting not at the the beginning of the gunslinger, (book 1) but at the end of the dark tower, (book 7). in short, new territory. So go into it with an open mind.

text: I hate to admit I'm a bit...mixed on this.  On one hand, despite some people here, I love the casting of Roland and The Man in Black (yes I'm totally fine with Roland being black, Idris Elba is one of the best actors in Hollywood).  I also really love the idea of this being a sequel of sorts to the final book (readers know what this means).    However...the tone of this doesn't really match up with the incredibly grim, dark tone of the books.  This seems a bit too glitzy and show-offy.  I'm also not getting the impression that this is a hard R movie, which it absolutely needs to be, perhaps more than the vast majority of R-rated films to come out in recent memory.  The Dark Tower deals with absolutely grotesque themes, extreme violence, insanely vulgar dialogue and more than a healthy serving of sex and nudity.  Making it appeal to a more mainstream audience would be a deathblow, in my mind.

text: Spoilers and opinion      Looks good. I understand why people are upset but having just re-read the gunslinger, adapting just that book into a film I think would be so boring. The medium for that story fits in a book. This movie being a sequel to the whole book series is starting out more action packed and the effects of all worlds coming down is emphasized clearly. Also, hopefully the Crimson King get portrayed as the big baddie that he's supposed to be (or at least referenced more, he only was talked about very minimally in throughout the series and only showed up at the end). With Jake drawing pics of the Gunslinger and all, I think it's portraying that he somewhat remembers the Gunslinger from previous cycles(called Shine or something in the movie) Hopefully Roland remembers also cause the whole reason he has to go through this journey again and again is because of his character and how he would be willing to let others die so he could reach his goal. I'm hoping this movie ends with Roland and Jake on a beach and a door in front of them...ready to Draw the others.

text: When I first heard that Idris Elba was being casted as Roland, I was skeptic (as many others), but I thought that Idris Alba is talented enough that this might actually work.  If they wanted to change Roland to be black...that's fine...whatever.  They do it all the time in Hollywood.  But after seeing this decision in action for the first time, I'm not as optimistic.  Major plot points from the books aside, I just don't think this works.  And this is coming from a huge Idris Elba fan.  Roland best resembled Clint Eastwood - which after all is who he was written after.  But Roland also resembles Denzel Washington's character from The Magnificent 7.  I think if they would've pursued that route as a character base, there wouldn't be 3/4 of the disappointed Dark Tower fans right now.  I hope I'm proven way wrong on this.  But unfortunately I think for once I will be right

The long version is, well, longer: It involves not only Deschain following a bad guy called The Man in Black (aka The Walkin‚Äô Dude, aka Randall Flagg) across the desert, a psychic boy named Jake Chambers (Tom Taylor), a woman in a wheelchair with dissociative identity disorder named Odetta/Detta who has tactical sex with a demon and uses the sieve of Eratosthenes to find prime numbers, a heroin addict named Eddie who fights a gun battle naked and defeats an insane train named Blaine with dad jokes. There‚Äôs also a place in New York called the Dixie Pig where cannibal vampire things eat people, and a place in Mid-World called Calla Bryn Sturgis that‚Äôs patrolled by robot wolves. And Oy, a smart, lovable, loyal, toddler-version-of-a-talking-animal who looks like a slinky raccoon and whose eyes are rimmed with gold and if you have read the entire series and your throat doesn‚Äôt lump up at the story of Oy, then you might as well just make a reservation at the Dixie Pig and let them eat your heart because you aren‚Äôt using it anyway.

text: *SPOILERS AHEAD*  I'll hold my full judgments for the actual movie, but a huge part of TDT story arc is Roland turning from this ruthless person who seeks the tower for unknown reasons (?), into someone who comes to find kinship and loyalty in the Ka Tet he "draws" along the way.   In fact, Roland's ruthless behavior in the first book is only overshadowed by The Man in Black. If you didn't understand his true motives, when you read the first chapter of the first book it feels like he brutally murders an unarmed farmer for nothing, and is forced to murder a woman who was cursed by the knowledge of the secret of death. Roland is partially insane because he gazed into Maerlyn's grapefruit for far too long. His sense of justice was distorted by it.      Idris Elba, on the other hand, seems like he's a hero fighting for "justice". I like his chiseled looks as much as the next person, but I agree that they should have made him look more haggard for this particular film. He feels like he exists outside of his decaying world, and is not a part of it.      Also, the interdimensionality gaps for characters like Jake have more horror and subtlety aspect in the books. I wish that they played Jake so that his visions were more disjointed and his behavior was more erratic before he resolved the break between worlds. I mean, the kid threw himself in front of a car and saw himself falling through a chasm of eternity. I don't just want other characters to feel like he was insane, I wish that the audience also felt  like HE could actually be totally insane. The confirmation of his "rantings" through an earthquake was a bit eyeroll for me.    Roland is awful chatty in this film and provides a lot of exposition, and I understand why people like that in movies but...    Thus far, it feels more like a straightforward action film with some jump scares interspersed and a DT flavor  Also, the tone seems kinda off... The books are horror/fantasy with a splash of sci fi. Marketing the movie as an action film just adds to the confusion. I wish this trailer were created more like a horror film and less like an action film.   In fact, to me, right now, Westworld feels more like TDT than TDT feels like TDT   I know trying to condense these books into something watchable has been a chore. I understand why they made certain choices and concede to big Hollywood on (probably a lot of) decisions.   I just hope they did not forget the face of their fathers.

text: (HERE BE BOOK SPOILERS)  To people who accuse book fans of 'whining' about casting of Idris Elba as Roland: you obviously don't understand what it means for the plot of the adaptation. It means that even if Eddie Dean and Detta/Odetta/Susannah Walker appear in the sequel (and I think it's a safe bet they won't appear in this one), the relationship between members of the ka-tet will likely lose in complexity in nuance. It won't be fraught with racism, bigotry and mutual distrust (unless Susannah is cast as a white supremacist or something?).  Similarly, it does not bode well for the portrayal of Gunslinger himself. Let me remind you that the book Roland is as anti-heroic as they come: he is obsessed with reaching the Tower and does pretty horrific things in order to achieve his goal. I guess the jury's out on this, but I just can't see the black lead character murdering an entire village or betraying Jake and letting him fall to his death. It would be ironic if casting a black actor as Roland would lead to the whitewashing of his character.  I'm well aware that this movie isn't intended as a faithful adaptation but rather a sequel to the book series. But turning Dark Tower into a straightforward, good vs. evil, black vs. white (har har) fantasy romp still does not feel right to me.  Still, when viewed on its own, this does look great. text: I actually read what King said about what this movie is. If you read the series, this is not that movie. It's based on what happens after the end of the storyline of the books. Which, to my understanding, was a perfect loop. Adding to the underlying despair of the story and our hero. Since none of the movie studios had the balls to bring the actual story to film, King now tells us that Deschain is no longer stuck in a loop, but that things change with each run through. Leaving us with a hope that the series did not originally embody, and what is sure to be the bitter taste of sell out in our mouths. It is not a reboot like Star Trek, as King would have us believe. But a departure from his original storyline, which robs us of what made this story what it was in the first place. Replacing despair with a sense of hope that things can change for the better. That Roland mayhap find peace. And escape his fate. Leaving our hero to abandon his post, fading from memory. All the while, trying to dupe the reader into believing that everything works out for the best in the great finality of it all. An end that in no way justifies the means...

text: For those that are not readers of King's works.  Walter. The man in black played by Matthew Mcconaughey is the same person as Flagg in The Stand.  Walter or Flagg is at fault for the majority of horrible events happen in King's works. He moves through time and planes of existence either destroying out of enjoyment or for moving the pieces in place to obtain power or change events.  98% of King's works have to do with The Dark Tower. The readers of the novels would tell you that it's just as if not more epic than the Game of Thrones novels.   Many characters from King's works pop up in reference or as characters themselves.  Dark Tower has always been the focus. There are very few works that are not attached to The Dark Tower.   IT is a demon from the same world as Roland. text: Ok, here's my take. SPOILER ALERT BLANK SPACE    I had always assumed that after each restart things only changed a tiny bit. A myriad of tiny changes that will eventually lead to Roland's salvation. But that's always been my own assumption. What if things actually change A LOT each time? What if every time Roland goes after the tower it's almost a completely different story? Maybe Eddie and Susannah never even show up this time around, and are left to enjoy their reward for their actions in the last loop. This is a continuation after all, not an adaptation.  I'm just as interested to see how the Roland/Detta dynamic will now work as anyone else (if she shows up), but it's also true that not many actors are of a caliber to play Roland. Idris is definitely on a very short list. I'm very much looking forward to seeing what he does with the character.

text: "There are other worlds than this": For all of the haters (before the movie is even released!) please consider this when watching movie adaptations of Stephen King's books. He's already written the books; he's told "his" side of the story, so when he signs over movie rights he's allowing another creative entity to take from his work and tell the story from "their" point of view. If he's OK with it, so am I. And once I've seen the "new" point of view, it's then and only then, that I can judge it on its own merits or failings. Either way, I still have SK's masterpieces on my bookshelves to visit again and again, like dear old friends.

text: When I first read these books some years ago, I found that though Mr. King might be a fine writer he knew little or nothing about firearms.   In the first few seconds of this trailer, we see the Gunslinger perform an impossible feat. Somehow tossing a load of six cartridges into the air, and then moving his revolver to intercept them and perform a reload in mid-air, as it were.  Now this would be vastly unlikely under any circumstance, but the revolvers pictured are solid-frame single-action models which would NOT have a swing-open cylinder (were it not for CGI).   Rather, these weapons are loaded singly through a "loading gate" on the right side of the frame. One round at a time.

The story of Jake, Roland, and the Man in Black all happened in the book The Gunslinger.  Jake coming through the portal in the house doesn't happen until The Drawing of the Three.  For that matter, where the hell were Eddie and Susannah during all this?  I couldn't care less if they cast Jackie Chan as Roland of Gilead as long as they're faithful to the story. text: As I'm currently reading (again) chapter VII of the Dark Tower series, after watching this trailer all I can say is: "What in the names of all Gods have you done, Hollywood?"  I mean, this looks very much like the typical film adaptation of a good book: You take the names of the main characters, some elements of the plot and then re-write the script completely differently so that the original book is nearly impossible to recognize. Yeah, we're been told that this is a sequel, so this is supposed to be the chapter VIII? Nope! From what I saw in this trailer I find basically no reason to go and see this film. For me, it just isn't a part of the Dark Tower story I have read and loved for so many years. It might be a good film. Even great. But Dark Tower? Nah, just and reflection of a dark tower in some insignificant parallel universe.

text: 0:39 Ah, that's funny. That's Timberline Lodge, a ski resort up on Mount Hood not far from where I live, though it's better known as the exterior of the Overlook Hotel in The Shining. The interiors were shot in a studio in England, and the real inside of Timberline is actually a lot cooler, though less mind-bending.  Fun fact - the Kubrick film used Room 237 instead of Room 217 from the book at the request of the lodge, because Timberline HAS no room 237, and they were afraid patrons would be afraid to sleep in a room associated with the movie. Ironic twist - room 217 is now Timberline's most requested suite.

text: I really don't care about Roland being black or not. I really don't. I also like Idris Elba so I believe he's a fine character choice.  I really, really care about what appears to be a butchering of the main themes; mystery, despair, struggle against futility and destiny. I believe Roland (in the books), and by extension the entire series, to be an allegory to 'Do not go gentle into that good night'.   This trailer feels like a teenage movie something akin to the Maze Runner etc. and that depresses me. Even if it is meant to be Roland on the next time around (an idea that would give loads of creative licence), it should still have the same atmospheric feel to it.  Obviously I can't be sure until the movie is released but as of right now, I'm worried that it has been dumbed-down and bastardised.

text: Sorry. I've been looking forward to a solid film adaptation of these novels since I finished them years ago. It's quite obvious this isn't it. This work could be so well done. The trailer tells me it isn't. What I see is a cheaply made, fast-tracked, hollowed out version of some of King's deepest, most personal work. There were seven novels. No way to compress them into one flimsy movie without losing everything they were really about. Love Idris Elba, but he is no Roland; nor is Matthew McConaughey The Man in Black. And it's nothing to do with race at all. Just poor casting, evident weak characterization and watered down storytelling. So disappointed with the look of this. Bummer.

text: I'm currently going through the series again and am early in book 7. Well, the movie appears to be VERY different from the books...mostly in important ways and not the fairly trivial one that most people seem hung up on. Since the story seems to have been entirely revised for the big screen it is hard to say how I think it will come out. I loved that the trailer showed Roland reloading. I've wanted to see that sort of thing ever since I first heard that they might make movies of the Dark Tower books. Elba and Mcconaughey are both phenomenal actors so that is promising. The director, Nikolaj Arcel, seems to be competent if not particularly experienced or brilliant. The August release date is an unfortunate red flag, but I'm cautiously optimistic at this point.

text: If you read a lot of Stephen King's commentaries about the early days of him writing the series, it's fairly... bland. The first book (The Gunslinger) is also fairly bland compared to the others. I remember him reminiscing in one of his novels about various trips to a cabin in the summer during stormy weather, coming back to the original manuscript and touching it up to the final version of The Gunslinger that's available today. To those just watching this this trailer for the first time thinking for a great action movie, there's a TON of backstory and exposition that makes this universe come to life. This first movie is more of a re-imagining of the series than it is a faithful adaptation. This is coming from someone who has read the Dark Tower series once per year for the past 15 years.  That being said, this trailer has me fairly excited to see how this iconic series is re-imagined in our modern age. For reference, King started writing this series in the '70s and finally finished it in the early 2000's. I won't spoil things for anyone who hasn't read the series, but it goes on some fairly strange tangents (that sandwich sauce [book 6]). Thumbs up if you get that reference.  I feel like this movie is going to pay homage to the original novel (The Gunslinger), but take obvious liberties as it's "supposed" to take place after the novels (ie, Roland in NY before ever meeting Eddie). The whole novel series is fairly complex in its timelines. Feel free to debunk me on this.

The Tower is famously linking All realities. The iteration HAD to be different. Once this is understood, The Susannah excuse is not quite valid (it would have been, had the movie been a REPLAY of the Book) ... text: ***SPOILERS***  This is not following the story lines from the book. If you finished the series, you should understand that and what the Horn of Eld means, and the last thing Gan says to Roland. This film is a continuation of the story, as Roland has been through the same cycle many, many times and always makes the wrong choices.   This time around, he has the Horn of Eld, which is the last remaining artifact of All World That Was, aside from Roland's guns. It has the potential to change his path, as having the Horn means almost the entire timeline of the DT could have massive changes. This is why things are happening differently this time, and why this should almost certainly be Roland's last journey to the Tower before he is granted peace.  I figure it at least gives us the chance of a better ending for Roland. He deserves some redemption.

If it's exactly the same, then what's the point in even watching it?  Forget about the source of the story and judge the film based on the merits. To me the trailer looks pretty amazing.  Originally, I was a little curious about the casting choice for Roland. This was only because it would change the dynamic between he and a certain "drawn" individual.   After some reflection, in the end, I don't think that it's really that detrimental to the story.  I hope the film does amazing. I want them to see it through to the end.  I still think I would have preferred it done as a series on HBO. With what they've done with "Ice and Fire" it seems that they could've done wonders with this as well.

text: Anyone who has been following the news for this movie since it was pitched in 08 (maybe 09?) know then that this IS NOT A RENDITION OF THE ORIGINAL 7! Stephen King himself approved of Idris Elba being Roland, and has stated this movie is a continuation AFTER the 7th book.  Any fans of the original books KNOW what happens to Roland at the end of the seventh, and this movie takes place after the last sentence of the last book. King has even stated that Roland does posses the Horn of Eld, so that should be a sign to people what this one is about!   We already know that Jake died once (though I think he died 3 times in the series all together), and we know that there is a nexus of multiple universes, and that at the end of the seventh book Susannah, Eddie, Jake (and it is implied Oy) have fading memories of what occurred. It wouldn't be surprising if the memories Jake is experiencing in this trailer are the memories he is trying to hold on of his last trip with Roland.  Alright no more spoilers! I'm done.

text: For anyone unfamiliar with the original story this looks fantastic. For those who have read the books, yes, Roland should be white and yes, changing his race does have a significant impact on the story because of racial elements within it that will have to be changed. With that said, Idris is an amazing actor, and from the trailer, it looks like he has absolutely nailed the part, as well as anyone possibly could with physical traits that disagree with the author's description (and die-hards' preconceived notions) of the character. Every movie adaptation changes parts of the story, and as long as they are able to do this while keeping the feel and the overall plot somewhat true to the original (which remains to be seen) I don't think this is a problem. The only issue I have with it is possibly the motivation of the studio to cast Idris. If they cast him because they felt he was the best person for the job, and that casting him was worth the blowback from the picky fans and the changes that needed to be made to the story because of the expectation of a great performance from him, then I applaud them for taking a risk and not excluding him on the basis of race. If, on the other hand, they chose him _because_ he is black, to make a statement to those who try to make everything about race and to gain popularity from those who complain about racism where it doesn't exist, then I think it was a poor choice. Unfortunately, we may never know why they did it, and we will just have to wait and see how true to the source the movie ends up being, and whether it's still a solid movie despite its departure from its roots.

text: It‚Äôs important to distinguish the movie franchise from the books. The movies are not a straight up adaption of the books, they are a sequel of sorts.   SPOILER WARNING SPOILER WARNING  At the end of DT7, Roland reaches the top of the Tower and is horrified to learn that he‚Äôs completed his journey many, many times before. The voice from the tower, which I presume to be Gan, says ‚ÄúThis is your promise that things may be different, Roland ‚Äì that there may yet be rest.‚Äù He is pushed through the doorway back to the beginning of his trek across the Mohaine Desert, but this time he has the Horn of Eld. This is significant, as the Horn of Eld is a symbol of Roland‚Äôs lineage, his purpose and his companions. He was destined to wind the horn as he made his way through Can-Ka-No-Rey (the field of roses at the base of the tower), but in the books, he loses it when his friend, Cuthbert, gets killed at the Battle of Jericho Hill.  Now Roland has the Horn of Eld, it means that everything can change. With the Horn of Eld, he may be less inclined to watch his ka-tet sacrifice themselves for his quest. This is why the trailer shows things that do not happen in the books. Jake doesn‚Äôt die to get to Mid-World, he finds a doorway, like he does in The Sailor arc of The Drawing of the Three, and I‚Äôm willing to bet that Roland doesn‚Äôt make the same choice as before when it comes down to saving Jake or finding the Tower.  I liked quite a lot about the trailer. I enjoyed seeing parts of Mid-World, the Mohaine Desert, Gilead and the portal. I liked the glow in Roland‚Äôs eyes and his guns when he fires. It‚Äôs a good compromise between the bombardier-blue eyes he has in the books, and it also highlights that Roland‚Äôs abilities aren‚Äôt entirely natural to new audiences. Roland looks badass in his outfit, but it does seem a little too pristine for someone who has spent a good chunk of time wandering across an inhospitable desert.  There were a few things I didn‚Äôt like. Jake shouldn‚Äôt have to explain the importance of the Tower to Roland, and Roland should need no encouragement to reach it. However, judging by the obvious ADR done on the dialogue, I do wonder whether that was added to the trailer to explain the basic story. Explaining the Dark Tower to someone can be exhausting, as many fans will attest.   Also, what were the orc looking things fighting for Walter? They clearly aren‚Äôt Taheen. They don‚Äôt look much like slow mutants to me either. These might be a new addition to the series as cannon fodder for Roland and Jake. That might be a bad call, as the DT books had action in them, but was generally a much slower-paced affair. I‚Äôm hoping they don‚Äôt turn it into an action film with less character development.  That town they were in at the end, that's either Tull or Pricetown, right? Am I forgetting any other settlements?

text: Roland is described as not only looking like Clint Eastwood but also looking eerily like the author himself, Stephen King, who resides on the key world. Idris looks nothing like SK, Roland, nor Eastwood.  Roland is based on a real French paladin, does that imply that the original Roland, Charlemagne, and possibly Arthur Eld are also darker skinned? Its very likely this will never be addressed, as a fan of the books this is unacceptable, you cannot change the story and characters without it reflecting on the background canon and mythology.  \\   Back to the original Roland, his king was the aforementioned Charlemagne. In the year 1,000 A.D. the locals dug up Charlemagne's dead body, they feared that the Devil would rise up to Earth and it would be the battle of Armageddon, so they needed the dead king to fight and save the world. This is real history.  Rolands weapons and horn are based on the real Roland's; Durendal and Olifant. These were real, these are real, so to say that its a new universe and those things never happened or they happened in a different way is a cop out, it doesn't address the how or the why, just what happened much later.  \\  Odetta Holmes is also based a real person, if they change Roland then there is a good chance they will change, remove, or otherwise alter her character. This would be insulting to Odetta Holmes and the struggles she went through to realize in her various works of art and activism.

text: SPOILER ALERT!!!!!   : : : "The finite mind cannot grasp the infinite..." - The Man In Black.  This has never been more true than now reading all the hate from (fans?) of King's work.  King himself warned us of this before the Coda at the end of the final Dark Tower book. He warns us not to continue reading. He warns us that nothing he writes within the Tower could possibly fulfill what great expectations we, (the constant reader) have for Roland at the Tower. But we insist. We are Tower junkies like Roland himself. So, King writes it because we MUST see what is at the Tower. And that is the point of the ending. WE are the reason Roland is thrust back to the beginning. In essence, WE the constant reader, we FORCE Roland into that Tower when King warned us to let it go. We did it anyway.   Now...this time Roland has the horn. I believe that the horn represents hope. I believe that this being the final time around, Roland carries the horn as a symbol of hope. He will right the wrongs from the times before, hence NOT allow Jake to die in pursuit of the Tower. The horn will balance out Roland's obsession for the Tower, and he will make the right choices. In fact, an alternate ending may come of this, where Roland reaches the Dark Tower, is granted entry, but simply walks away.   Take care of your Ka-tet, (the people in your life that matter most), and let go of the obsession which resonates from the Dark Tower.   I thankee sai. Long days and pleasant nights.   <3

text: what truly makes me feel sad, dejected and disappointed is not that this movie doesn't follow the plot or lore of the dark tower, but that because this movie was made, we will never see stephen king's actual vision of the dark tower realized as a movie.   The dark tower is just to cool not to tell it exactly the way stephen king told it. the lord of the rings movies followed tolkiens plot almost exactly to the letter, and they are good movies. to mangle or simplify the lord of the rings would have been seen as blasphemous, but people dont have the same respect for stephen king as they do for tolkien, but they should, the dark tower is one of the very best fantasy epics of all time, up there with lord of the rings.  They should have made the movie about the first book in the series. if the audience liked it they can keep making sequels, the way harry potter movies are handled  they should NOT have tried to condense its plot and themes into a single movie, the result is clearly a neutered, simplified and quite frankly crummy facsimile.  I dont really care who stars in it as long as they perform their roles well. its not about casting. this whole concept is flawed. Stephen king should be more protective of his intellectual property.  you just watch, this movie will tank

text: As a long time fan of the books, I pretty much have to see this, but I'm definitely either gonna love or totally hate it. I have a question though, Does this seem like a friggin harry potter movie to anyone else? or at least somewhere between Potter and Tomorrow-land? even down to the trailer background music, not that I have a problem with the potter series, just not my style, which is probably what I liked about dark tower, It kinda felt like my harry potter series, especially when describing it to someone who had never heard of it. Whereas that series got like eight movies, and it had less overall pages than dark tower, and they didn't feel the need to change large aspects of their story. this just screams PG-13, like a lot of the decisions on the changes weren't "artistic" as much as profitable, I get it, it's a "sequel".... I probably don't just speak for myself when I say, I don't really want a sequel... after reading a story of over four thousand pages multiple times, I liked the story the way it was, ya know, good...I guess my point is, if you used some of your precious time to read this, is that the twilight people get their series, the Hunger games, the divergent or whatever, get theirs, and this is what we get? text: I was 100% positive that Matthew Mcconaughey was Roland and Idris Elba was the man in black. I recall thinking what outstanding casting choices those were. I'm shocked to see the parts were casted the other way around. It has nothing to do with race.. certain actors just fit certain roles better. Idris imo has a very limited repertoire as an actor, but he plays one-dilemsional characters extremely well, especially bad guys. Roland is a outstandingly completed figure, Mcconaughey would really have to bring his "A" game, but he would fit the part well. This is kind of like casting a movie about Martin L. King with the Doctor himself being a white guy. Or a Ghandi movie with Ghandi as a mexican. Now obviously Roland not being white doesn't approach that same level, but it's still the same brand of silliness. It's a shame Clint Eastwood is far to old to play Roland, it would of been one of the all time greatest fits of actor to character. Elba plays basically the same exact guy in every movie he has ever been in, I must say I'm not looking forward to his portrayal as the Gunslinger, as I already know exactly how it will go. Should of waited for Denzel.

text: I was skeptical as all hell when it was announced that a Black actor would play a character who I have known to be based on a White person (described as Clint Eastwood mixed with a little Stephen King by the author) since I first read the first part of a novel that would consume me for decades nearly thirty years ago, but after seeing the trailer, I think that I can deal with Mr. Elba. He is a very good actor and I think that he can pull off this role. I always imagined Matthew McConaughey as Eddie, but whatever.   I know a lot of people are up in arms, but see if this makes sense to you - he's not Roland as you know him, he's an alternate Roland: the same, yet different. It's like James Bond - they're all James Bond, the same and yet different.   I also like how they've handled the plot - instead of this being based on the books that we've read, this is (SPOILER ALERT!!) Roland's next reincarnation on his perhaps-not-any-longer eternal quest to save the Tower.   I'm jazzed for this movie to come out and I'm hoping as much as anyone else that it's amazing. The characters and the world that we fell in love with while reading the series deserve nothing less than awesomeness.

text: Hmmm...I'm provisionally on-board, though with serious misgivings.  Idris Elba has the chops, though I'm not sure the presence, to pull-off Roland.  Jeffery Wright would have been a much better choice.  And while Matthew McConaughey certainly seems to check-off many of the boxes, he's just plain wrong for Randall Flagg.  I think an unknown actor with some sort of ephemeral, otherworldly quality would fit the bill.  As for Jake, if what we saw was any indication, they just plain fucked-up with him.  Big time.  As for the plot and world changes, I don't know man.  What they did to the story looks like it could be interesting, but it seems such an overhaul and simplification...I don't see how it could possibly do the original story justice.  Plus, I don't think the filmmakers understand it's a dying, worn-out _universe_, not just world, that Roland comes from.  I guess I'll just try to forget the books while watching this.  That seems to be about the only way there's any chance of enjoying movie adaptations about 95% of the time.

text: Why the fck is everyone complaining about a movie that's not even out yet ? It's just a trailer dangit ! Trailers can be bad !  Lots of people are complaining abut the movie for no reason other than it was not the exact adaptation they wanted. And it's a garbage argument since, a movie like "The Shining" was a garbage adaptation but a GREAT movie. Did evryone just forget that there was no way that this one movie could adapt the whole 7 books ? I didn't read the books, and I don't care, I just want to see a good movie. text: If you've read the books, or better yet - read all seven of the books then listened to the first four narrated by Frank Muller, then read the last three and then repeat - the movie will never match that. But I expect this will be a great movie. At first it seems strange because in the books Roland is very obviously white.... but then thinking about it more I realize that no white man could take the place of Roland the way all of our imaginations have pictured. It may have been accidental or planned, but having Roland played by a man that virtually none of us would have imagined seems like a brilliant move. ¬†I'm looking forward to seeing the movie and I hope that people who have missed out on the magic of reading will be inspired to take another crack at it, because when it comes to the books of The Dark Tower......There are no other books than these.

text: The true genius of The Dark Tower series is how it literally ties together like half of all the King novels ever written.  Characters from The Stand (including King's favorite go to bad guy Randall Flagg), Hearts in Atlantis, Salem's Lot etc etc. are included throughout the seven novels.  An absolutely genius move on King's part financially, since to truly get the full force of the Dark Tower, you really did have to go back and read all of his older work that led up to this.
author: Brad C

text: For all those complaining about Idris Elba being cast as Roland Deschain, King himself seems perfectly happy with the decision, saying the following:   "I love it [Elba]. I think he's a terrific actor, one of the best working in the business now. For me the character is still the character. It's almost a Sergio Leone character, like the Man with No Name. He can be white or black, it makes no difference to me. I think it opens all kind of exciting possibilities for the backstory."  So there you have it. If the character's creator, (the one person that understands that character more than anyone else in the world), is satisfied with the casting, we really can't complain, now can we? Besides, Idris Elba looks pretty fucking cool as a space cowboy.

That is 40 years of truly being entertained by Mr. King(thank you) yet I was so excited to see this story come to life and was just so very disappointed. It could have been so much more. Please don't follow this series , let it stay written.

text: I expected too much from this movie. It shouldn't have been called The Dark Tower. I understand it's not really based on the books 1-7, but so much was left out - the symbolism, the becoming of Susannah, Eddie's drawing, the friggin' lobstrosities, Susan Delgado, even the bumbler Oy... and why was it all centered around Jake? It was more like a kids' movies. We've had enough movies like this lately. Stephen King's book series is a masterpiece and this movie doesn't do it justice. I really liked Idris Elba as Roland, though. And I can't imagine a better actor to play the man in black than Matthew McConaughey.

text: So, i'm seeing in the comments," its not as good as the books" ,etc.  Keep in mind that Sony picked this up and made it into a movie, so at the least, people that have no knowledge of the books that originated this movie will have at least had some contact  with the original content, despite lacking the robustness of the books. Here's another point: some people will go back for the books after seeing the movie. I, for one, have done such. I've also done it in the past to two other movies that Stephen King released.  Also, some people just have unrealistic expectations when it comes to entertainment. If Netflix, or Hulu picked this up, then, yeah - I could see the books being reproduced in seasons that would cover everything,  but Sony got it.  So the movie was done as it was.  Me? I enjoyed both.  I feel some just need to relax. You didnt like the movie?  That's your opinion. Others have. Besides, the movie put away over 100 million dollars in sales off a 60 million dollar budget. How bad was the movie if it made that much money ? And before you say anything, yes , Roland being black probably upset the die hard readers, but this doesn't surprise me at all.  Keep in mind the time line of these books, then divide that by Sony being involved.  In fact, i find it ironic for people to whine about something like this when I've seen this several times over in so many books and movies much older and better. The killing part is the end result was the same: a shit load of money being madeat the box office and a couple of butt hurt critics . Go figure.
